Had to see this one in a theater (IMAX, even) out of respect, but THE DIAL OF DESTINY (terrible title) ranks fourth of all the Indy movies, for me. It hit some nice nostalgia buttons, especially the ending, but mostly it felt like going through the motions of the types of things that happen in Indiana Jones movies. I was pretty surprised to find sections of the film to be boring. The de-aging stuff is not completely convincing, and we (writers, and now actors) are striking because if the technology improves (or even if it doesn’t) they could just put dead actors in movies instead of hiring living ones. And this installment is fairly humor-free, which is a bummer because that’s what made the first three movies so much fun. I loved James Mangold’s LOGAN but here he just seems to be trying to copy Spielberg’s moves. Of course my opinions on these films don’t really matter, because TEMPLE OF DOOM is my favorite of the bunch. Overall it’s been a good ride and I’m glad they made a fifth one to help erase #4. Goodnight, Dr Jones!

When I was in high school in San Diego, my drama teacher was old friends with actress Joyce DeWitt, who hit the big time with the television sitcom THREE’S COMPANY. So a trip was arranged for the class to see a taping of the extremely popular show. A bus was chartered to take the class to Television City, where the program that ushered in “jiggle tv” was produced. But when we got there, the studio audience was overbooked and there was no room for us. The compromise, since we traveled all that way, was to let us sit in an empty studio (the same one that was the home to THE CAROL BURNETT SHOW, MATCH GAME and THE PRICE IS RIGHT, among many others) and watch the performance on monitors. It was exciting to be watching a nationwide phenomenon being taped live, but weird that we weren’t in the room where it was happening. But then, after the taping concluded, when the actors were probably tired and would rather go home, Joyce DeWitt, John Ritter and Suzanne Somers sauntered into the studio and sat down on the stage, graciously chatting with us and answering questions. They were all so sweet (years later I would get to interact with John in a more significant way, and he was super nice in that instance as well). Suzanne really made herself comfortable during the visit, laying on her side holding up her head with one hand, like she was posing for a sexy pic (she was probably just exhausted). The bus ride home was full of talk about Suzanne’s crazy tight pants. I’ll never forget my friend Tina saying two words that I had never heard strung together before. RIP Suzanne Somers, you may have been a nerd’s dream girl in AMERICAN GRAFFITI, but you were my first “camel toe.”
